23 provision imposing the same penalty for a person who negligently stores or leaves a firearm at
24 a similar location from which a person who is less than 21 years of age may obtain the
25 firearm.
26 Existing law authorizes a child who is 14 years of age or older and who, among other
27 requirements, has a valid hunting license, to handle, possess or control a: (1) rifle or shotgun;
28 or (2) firearm capable of being concealed upon the person. However, existing law provides
29 that the rifle or shotgun must not be a fully automatic firearm. (NRS 202.300) Section 3 of
30 this bill prohibits a child who is 14 years of age or older from handling, possessing or
31 controlling a semiautomatic shotgun or semiautomatic centerfire rifle.
32 Under certain circumstances, existing law authorizes a child who is 14 years of age or
33 older to handle, possess or control a rifle or shotgun that is not a fully automatic firearm at his
34 or her residence. (NRS 202.300) Section 3: (1) provides that the rifle or shotgun must not be a
35 semiautomatic shotgun or semiautomatic centerfire rifle; and (2) requires that the rifle or
36 shotgun, while not in use, must remain unloaded and stored in a securely locked container
37 under the possession of certain persons.
38 Existing law provides that a person who barters or sells a pistol, revolver or firearm
39 capable of being concealed to a child who is less than 18 years of age, with reckless
40 disregard of the age of the child or with knowledge or reason to know that the child is
41 less than 18 years of age, is guilty of a category B felony punishable by imprisonment in
42 the state prison for a minimum term of not less than 1 year and a maximum term of not
43 more than 6 years, and may be further punished by a fine of not more than $5,000. (NRS
44 202.310) Section 3.5 of this bill provides that a person who sells or barters a
45 semiautomatic centerfire rifle or semiautomatic shotgun to a person who is less than 21
46 years of age, with reckless disregard of the age of the person or with knowledge or
47 reason to know that the person is less than 21 years of age, is guilty of a category B
48 felony and is subject to the same penalties.
49 Section 2 of this bill applies certain definitions prescribed by existing law to section 1.
